  "prompt": "How do you clear your Hotmail inbox?",
  "response": "Clearing your Hotmail (now Outlook.com) inbox can be done in several ways, depending on what you want to achieve and how many emails you want to get rid of. Here's a breakdown of the common methods:\n\n**1. Deleting Individual Emails:**\n\n*   **Select the email:** Click the circle to the left of the email you want to delete. A checkmark will appear.\n*   **Click the Delete button:**  Look for the trash can icon at the top of your inbox, or right-click the selected email and choose \"Delete.\"\n\n**2. Deleting Multiple Emails:**\n\n*   **Select multiple emails:** You can do this in a few ways:\n    *   **Check the boxes next to each email:** Click the circle to the left of each email you want to delete.\n    *   **Select a range of emails:** Click the box next to the first email in the range. Then, hold down the **Shift** key and click the box next to the last email in the range.  This will select all emails in between.\n    *   **Select all emails on the current page:**  At the top of your inbox, there might be a checkbox next to a label like \"Select all\".  Check this box to select all the emails visible on the current page.\n*   **Click the Delete button:**  Once you've selected the emails, click the trash can icon or right-click and choose \"Delete.\"\n\n**3. Emptying a Folder (Including the Inbox) Completely:**\n\n*   **Right-click the folder:** In the left navigation pane, right-click the \"Inbox\" (or any other folder you want to empty).\n*   **Select \"Empty folder\":**  Choose the \"Empty folder\" option from the menu that appears.\n*   **Confirm:**  You'll usually be prompted to confirm that you want to permanently delete all items in the folder.  Click \"OK\" or \"Empty\" to proceed.  **Be very careful with this option, as it's irreversible without a backup!**\n\n**4. Using Filters and Rules to Automate Deletion:**\n\n*   **Create Rules (Highly Recommended for Recurring Emails):**\n    *   **Right-click an email from the sender you want to filter.**\n    *   **Select \"Create rule\".**\n    *   **Define the rule:**  You can set conditions based on the sender, subject, or other criteria.\n    *   **Choose the action:**  Select \"Delete\" or \"Move to folder\" (like the Junk Email folder).  Moving to Junk is often better at first, so you can make sure you're not accidentally deleting something important.\n    *   **Save the rule:** The rule will now automatically apply to future emails that match the criteria.\n\n*   **Use Filters to Quickly Sort and Delete:**\n    *   **Sort by Sender, Subject, etc.:** At the top of your inbox, look for options to sort your emails (e.g., by sender, subject, date received).\n    *   **Select and Delete:** Once sorted, you can easily select a large group of emails from the same sender or with a similar subject and delete them.\n\n**5. Using Sweep:**\n\n*   **Select an Email:** Select an email from the sender you want to sweep.\n*   **Click Sweep:** At the top of the window, select \"Sweep\".\n*   **Choose an option:** This feature lets you automatically delete all messages from a certain sender, keep only the latest message, or block all future messages from that sender.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Deleted Items Folder:** When you delete emails, they are usually moved to the \"Deleted Items\" folder (also sometimes called \"Trash\" or \"Bin\").  They are *not* permanently deleted until you empty that folder.  To permanently remove the emails, you need to go to the \"Deleted Items\" folder and empty it.\n*   **Recoverable Items:**  Sometimes, even after emptying the \"Deleted Items\" folder, you might be able to recover emails for a short period, especially if you have Outlook.com Premium (now Microsoft 365). Look for a link like \"Recover deleted items\" in the Deleted Items folder.\n*   **Backup:**  Before deleting a large number of emails, especially from important senders, consider backing up your email account.  Microsoft doesn't natively offer easy backups of entire mailboxes, but you can use a third-party email client like Outlook (desktop version) configured with your account and then export a .pst file, or look into third-party backup services.\n*   **Unsubscribe:**  Instead of constantly deleting emails from unwanted senders (like newsletters), unsubscribe from their mailing lists.  Look for an \"Unsubscribe\" link at the bottom of the email.\n*   **Be Careful!** Double-check what you are deleting before you confirm. It's easy to accidentally delete important emails.\n\n**In summary, the best way to clear your inbox depends on your specific needs:**\n\n*   **For a few emails:**  Individual deletion is fine.\n*   **For many emails from the same sender:**  Create a rule or use Sweep.\n*   **For emptying the entire inbox:**  Empty the folder (but be *very* careful!).\n*   **For ongoing inbox management:** Set up rules to automatically filter and delete unwanted emails.\n",
